1 SECTION 3. IC 35-44.1-1-2.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
2 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
3 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 2.5. (a) As used in this section,
4 "gratuity" means a payment made to a public servant after an
5 official act as a reward or token of appreciation. However, the
6 term does not include:
7 (1) a good or service that is:
8 (A) subject to a reporting requirement; or
9 (B) otherwise authorized;
10 under a rule or code of ethics that applies to the donor or
11 public servant;
12 (2) a good or service having a de minimis value of less than
13 one hundred dollars ($100);
14 (3) an item that is primarily ceremonial or commemorative,
15 such as a plaque, trophy, certificate, framed photo, or similar
16 item;
17 (4) a political contribution subject to IC 3-9-2 that is reported
18 in accordance with applicable law;
19 (5) salary, wages, a bonus, or any other form of work related
20 compensation:
21 (A) from the governmental entity that employs the public
22 servant; and
23 (B) that the public servant is legally authorized to receive;
24 or
25 (6) an offer of employment that is not offered as a reward for
26 an official act performed by a public servant.
27 (b) As used in this section, "public servant" includes a former
28 public servant.
29 (c) A person who provides a gratuity to a public servant, with
30 the intent to reward the public servant for an official act
31 performed by the public servant for the person in the public
32 servant's official capacity, commits providing an unlawful gratuity
33 to a public servant, a Class A misdemeanor. However, the offense
34 is a Level 6 felony if the fair market value of the gratuity is at least
35 seven hundred fifty dollars ($750).
36 (d) A public servant who:
37 (1) solicits or accepts a gratuity from another person; and
38 (2) either:
39 (A) solicits the gratuity as a reward for; or
40 (B) knows or reasonably should know that the gratuity is
41 offered as a reward for;
42 an official act performed by the public servant for the person
